AB  - Abstract: Educational Robotics and Virtual STEM Learning Environments: Tools for Engaging Future Innovators presents an integrated framework for designing, implementing, and validating robotics- and simulation-based STEM education at scale. The book unifies learning sciences with engineering practice: embodied cognition and constructionism provide the pedagogical foundation; software–hardware architectures and virtual laboratories supply safe, instrumented spaces for inquiry; and assessment science converts artefacts and telemetry into dependable evidence of learning. Across six chapters, the volume formalizes competencies (computational thinking, engineering design, scientific modelling, collaboration, and ethical AI literacy), maps them to observable indicators, and aligns progressions from primary to university. It specifies rubrics, automated testing pipelines, and portfolio-based credentialing; proposes privacy-by-design analytics and fairness probes; and details procurement, teacher professional development, and programme quality assurance. Global caselets (resource-rich and resource-limited contexts) demonstrate portable design patterns—hybrid ER/VLE sequences, digital twins for sim-to-real transfer, and human–AI co-orchestration for feedback at classroom scale. By coupling open benchmarks and reproducibility with policy guardrails, the book offers researchers, practitioners, and policymakers a rigorous, evidence-centred playbook for cultivating capable, creative, and ethically grounded innovators. Keywords: educational robotics, virtual laboratories, digital twins, computational thinking, engineering design, constructionism, embodied cognition, learning analytics, formative assessment, rubrics, micro-credentials, equity and access, privacy-by-design, algorithmic fairness, teacher professional development, human–AI co-orchestration, simulation-to-real transfer, open benchmarks, reproducibility, STEM education
