AB  - This chapter explores the integration of metaverse technologies—particularly virtual reality (VR) and digital twins—into mechanical engineering education and industrial training. As immersive technologies advance, they offer compelling alternatives to traditional laboratory-based instruction by enhancing accessibility, learner engagement, and procedural understanding. This chapter begins with a comprehensive review of VR’s transformative role in mechanical engineering education, emphasizing its applications in simulation-based training environments. Two empirical studies are presented to evaluate the practical impacts of VR on cognitive load and learning outcomes. The first examines a VR-based composite manufacturing laboratory, revealing significant reductions in mental and physical demands compared to traditional laboratories. The second compares VR with video-based instruction for industrial robotics training, demonstrating greater learner engagement and reduced cognitive effort in the VR condition. Additionally, this chapter addresses key challenges associated with the adoption of VR and metaverse platforms, including motion sickness, user adaptation, and limited haptic feedback. Collectively, these findings underscore the potential of immersive technologies to modernize mechanical engineering education through scalable, interactive, and pedagogically effective training environments.
