Y2  - 2026/05/14
AB  - The rapid evolution of unmanned aerial vehicles (drones) is revolutionizing various industrial applications, and their integration into education presents a unique opportunity for comprehensive STEM learning. This paper proposes a curriculum framework that harnesses drones as a versatile platform for integrated STEM education, bridging engineering design, computer programming, and real-world applications. Drawing inspiration from two industrial research projects—one on autonomous drone-based inspection systems for thermal power plant boilers and another on generating synthetic data using digital twins of industrial instruments—we demonstrate how advanced technologies can be adapted for classroom use. Our curriculum is structured into sequential modules that guide students through the process of assembling a modular drone kit, programming autonomous navigation in confined and challenging environments, and implementing computer vision algorithms for defect detection. In doing so, learners engage with fundamental STEM concepts such as aerodynamics, sensor integration, control systems, and machine learning. This hands-on, project-based approach not only cultivates technical proficiency and interdisciplinary problem solving but also fosters critical thinking, creativity, and collaborative skills among students. Furthermore, by simulating real-world industrial challenges, the framework provides educators with a robust model for professional development and curriculum integration. Ultimately, this integrated approach highlights the transformative potential of drone technology to make STEM education more engaging, relevant, and aligned with current industry practices, thereby preparing students to meet future technological challenges.
