AB  - Current crises illustrate the responsibility of the education system to educate its students with the knowledge and skills needed to meet the requirements of an increasingly complex, digital, and volatile world. The energy transition represents a current crisis in which human-centred engineering solutions are essential. This paper outlines how two courses within a master's program use challenge-based learning and co-creation as methods to intertwine research and teaching. Both courses are split into theoretical sessions followed by group projects centred on the energy transition. This allows students not only to attain the necessary theoretical knowledge but also gives them practical experience in prototyping, user-centred (software) design, and considering sustainable and social dimensions. In incremental cycles, the research data informs the courses and vice versa. This is a contribution to actively practised research transfer with society as well to the development of future-oriented methods, structures and formats in engineering education.
