AB  - This paper proposes a metaheuristic optimization approach to plan medical residency training in Austria that addresses the practical constraints and scale of real-world planning scenarios. The training for medical students is a complex planning task, due to complex regulations and individualized schedules, involving rotating through departments and switching hospitals. An optimal plan for hundreds of students and sometimes across multiple hospitals simultaneously is key to a high-quality, cost-efficient training. Currently, planning is manual, resulting in a high planning effort for hospitals. However, available automatic planning approaches found in literature are not applicable to the complex practical planning task in Austrian hospitals. This paper contributes an automatically optimized planning approach for residency training in real-life planning scenarios. The method is developed and evaluated with the use-case and dataset derived from an Austrian hospital. The results show the feasibility and optimization potential of the presented approach.
