AB  - Abstract“Lab on Chip” is no longer a thing of the future. Microfluidic devices grow in popularity not only in research and development but also in industrial applications. The precise controllability and characteristic phenomena of microfluidic devices are systematically used. Education institutions support these trends and offer courses covering physical basics, manufacturing methods, applications, phenomena, and possibilities. Hands-on experiences for students, however, are scarce. This article intends to present a way to overcome the high entry hurdle for using micro-apparatus in laboratory education by designing an ultra-concurrent laboratory for everybody interested, based on the instructional principles of constructive alignment and the actual learning outcomes in laboratory education. This work is embedded in the joint project CrossLab by four German universities to produce flexibly combinable laboratory experiments, which serve the engineering education for competencies of working world 4.0.
