AB  - Iron graded lattice structures have the potential to be employed in biodegradable temporary implants and play a key role in the reduction of stress shielding. In this work, two graded specimens made of lattices with two unit cell types, truncated octahedron (TO) and rhombitruncated octahedron (RTCO), were analysed under compression, by means of the finite element method. Specimens of different unit cell types were designed with different values of relative density. Graded unit cells were chosen in the design of graded lattice structures. The results show that, under compression, graded lattices can achieve the same mechanical properties as non-graded lattices with a lower relative density. The relative density is verified to be an important property, for comparison of results in different cell structures, where different relative densities can lead to similar compressive behaviours. An equivalent density parameter, proposed in the current work, can be used to interchange the unit cell types used in temporary implants, while maintaining the mechanical properties.
