AB  - Learning the basics of computer science and programming is an integral part of almost all STEM education paths. The resulting large number of students per course makes it difficult to handle individual teaching and presents lecturers with various problems. External circumstances, such as the spontaneous switch to remote teaching, further complicate course delivery. In this paper, we present an approach to alleviate some of the major issues, such as grading of student submissions and the ability to perform programming tasks remotely, without the need for students to install and set up software tools on their own devices. The concept will be applied for the first time in the winter term 22/23 in a course with about two hundred mechanical engineering students, offering the possibility for both load tests for server hardware and a user acceptance study for an integrated programming exercise and grading approach.
