BT  - Open Science in Engineering
SP  - 989
EP  - 1001
DO  - 10.1007/978-3-031-42467-0_92
UR  - https://app.dimensions.ai/details/publication/pub.1167550973
Y2  - 2026/05/14
AB  - Recently, Virtual Reality (VR) technology has found its way to the practical hands-on trainings, especially in engineering education. The number of traditional hands-on trainings on physical devices is moving to the virtual world increasingly, thanks to the board training possibility and reachability, advanced development of the 3D modelling technology and affordable VR de-vices. With the virtual training concept, a large-scale hands-on training of difficult, expensive, or dangerous scenarios can be adopted. Still, one simple question concerning training efficiency has to be answered, namely “How effective actually is a VR training?” In this work, we aimed to capture activity data that is generated during a VR training session. This captured data was then prepared and analyzed using the Cosine Similarity method, which is used to measure similarity of the trainee’s activity data and the trainer’s one. To ensure that the similarity values align with the skill improvement, the pretest–posttest and the System Usability Scale (SUS) analysis were adopted. The results suggest that the activity data analysis can be used as an evaluation approach of a VR training effectiveness.
