AB  - Laboratory experiments play a significant role in science and engineering education within university settings. Traditional hands-on labs provide a natural environment for enhancing practical skills. However, with the advent of Information and Communication Technology (ICT), virtual and remote labs have emerged as pivotal components in the fields of Science, Technology, Engineering, and Mathematics (STEM). In particular, this white paper focuses on enabling remote access to authentic lab equipment, leveraging cutting-edge computing and networking technologies to establish an environment where remote users can conduct the necessary hands-on experiments in the field of physics.The principal objective of this endeavor is to develop an interactive system that empowers first-year university students in the Physical Chemistry department to control and conduct remote hands-on physics experiments. This paper concentrates on the conception and implementation of a prototype, enabling students to access the experimental facilities of the laboratory via an internet network. This newfound flexibility eradicates temporal and spatial limitations, enhances student safety during hazardous experiments, and concurrently diminishes the costs associated with lab equipment procurement and maintenance. The primary focus of our research is centered on the development of an elastic pendulum, employing both static and dynamic methodologies.
